.TH AJAZZ 1 "April 2026" "ajazz 0.3.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
ajazz \- control the Ajazz AK35I V3 MAX keyboard display and lighting
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ajazz
[\fB\-v\fR|\fB\-q\fR]
.I command
[\fIoptions\fR]
.br
.B ajazz
\fB\-h\fR
.br
.B ajazz
.I command
\fB\-h\fR
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B ajazz
is an unofficial Linux command-line tool for controlling the Ajazz AK35I V3 MAX
keyboard (USB VID 0x0C45, PID 0x8009). It can synchronize the on-screen clock,
configure RGB key backlighting, and upload static images or animated GIFs to
the keyboard's 1.14-inch TFT display (240\[mu]135 pixels). No root access is
required when the provided udev rules are installed.

The keyboard's back switch must be set to \fBUSB\fR mode.
.SH GLOBAL OPTIONS
Global options must appear \fIbefore\fR the subcommand.
.TP
\fB\-v\fR, \fB\-\-verbose\fR
Print HID protocol debug messages.
.TP
\fB\-q\fR, \fB\-\-quiet\fR
Suppress all output except errors.
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB\-\-help\fR
Show help text and exit.
.SH COMMANDS
.SS list
List all HID interfaces detected for connected Ajazz keyboards.
.PP
.RS 4
.B ajazz list
.RE
.SS time
Synchronize the keyboard's on-board real-time clock to the system time.
The clock runs autonomously afterward and does not need repeated updates.
.PP
.RS 4
.B ajazz time
.br
.B ajazz time \-\-at \fITIME\fR
.RE
.TP
\fB\-\-at\fR \fITIME\fR
Set to a specific time instead of now.
.I TIME
may be \fBHH:MM:SS\fR (today's date) or \fBYYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SS\fR (ISO 8601).
.SS light
Configure RGB key backlighting. Settings are saved to flash and persist across
power cycles.
.PP
.RS 4
.B ajazz light
[\fB\-m\fR \fIMODE\fR] [\fB\-r\fR \fIN\fR] [\fB\-g\fR \fIN\fR] [\fB\-b\fR \fIN\fR]
[\fB\-\-rainbow\fR] [\fB\-\-brightness\fR \fIN\fR] [\fB\-\-speed\fR \fIN\fR] [\fB\-\-direction\fR \fIN\fR]
.RE
.TP
\fB\-m\fR, \fB\-\-mode\fR \fIMODE\fR
Lighting animation mode (default: \fBstatic\fR). May be a name or a hex value
\fB0x00\fR\(en\fB0x13\fR. Available modes:
.RS
.PP
\fBoff\fR, \fBstatic\fR, \fBsingleon\fR, \fBsingleoff\fR, \fBglitter\fR, \fBfalling\fR,
\fBcolourful\fR, \fBbreath\fR, \fBspectrum\fR, \fBoutward\fR, \fBscrolling\fR,
\fBrolling\fR, \fBrotating\fR, \fBexplode\fR, \fBlaunch\fR, \fBripples\fR,
\fBflowing\fR, \fBpulsating\fR, \fBtilt\fR, \fBshuttle\fR
.RE
.TP
\fB\-r\fR, \fB\-\-red\fR \fIN\fR
Red component 0\(en255 (default: 255).
.TP
\fB\-g\fR, \fB\-\-green\fR \fIN\fR
Green component 0\(en255 (default: 255).
.TP
\fB\-b\fR, \fB\-\-blue\fR \fIN\fR
Blue component 0\(en255 (default: 255).
.TP
\fB\-\-rainbow\fR
Enable multicolour cycling mode (overrides \-r/\-g/\-b values).
.TP
\fB\-\-brightness\fR \fIN\fR
Brightness level 0\(en5, where 0 is off and 5 is full (default: 5).
.TP
\fB\-\-speed\fR \fIN\fR
Animation speed 0\(en5, where 0 is slowest and 5 is fastest (default: 3).
.TP
\fB\-\-direction\fR \fIN\fR
Animation direction: 0=left, 1=down, 2=up, 3=right (default: 0).
.SS keys
Show or set per-key RGB lighting. Without write flags, displays the live
per-key colour state. With write flags, performs a read-modify-write cycle:
reads the current flash table, applies changes, and writes the result back.
.PP
.RS 4
.B ajazz keys
[\fB\-a\fR]
.br
.B ajazz keys
[\fB\-\-clear\fR] [\fB\-\-base\fR \fICOLOR\fR]
[\fB\-s\fR \fIKEY COLOR\fR] ...
[\fB\-\-hsv\fR \fIKEY H S V\fR] ...
[\fB\-b\fR \fIPCT\fR]
.RE
.TP
\fB\-a\fR, \fB\-\-all\fR
Show all 144 key slots, including those with zero RGB (default: only lit keys).
.TP
\fB\-\-clear\fR
Start from all-off instead of reading the current state. Use with \fB\-\-set\fR
or \fB\-\-hsv\fR to build a layout from scratch.
.TP
\fB\-\-base\fR \fICOLOR\fR|\fIR G B\fR
Start from a solid base colour instead of reading the current state. Accepts
a CSS color name, \fB#RRGGBB\fR hex, or three integers 0\(en255.
.TP
\fB\-s\fR, \fB\-\-set\fR \fIKEY\fR \fICOLOR\fR|\fIR G B\fR
Set the colour for \fIKEY\fR. Repeatable; entries are applied left-to-right,
later entries override earlier ones for the same key.
\fIKEY\fR accepts a single key name (\fBw\fR), a comma-separated list
(\fBw,a,s,d\fR), a named group (\fBwasd\fR), or a numeric light_index.
\fICOLOR\fR accepts a CSS color name (\fBred\fR, \fBrebeccapurple\fR),
\fB#RRGGBB\fR hex, or three integers \fIR G B\fR (each 0\(en255).
.TP
\fB\-\-hsv\fR \fIKEY H S V\fR
Set the colour for \fIKEY\fR using QMK-style 8-bit HSV. \fIH\fR 0\(en255
(0=red, 85=green, 170=blue), \fIS\fR 0\(en255, \fIV\fR 0\(en255.
Applied after all \fB\-\-set\fR entries.
.TP
\fB\-b\fR, \fB\-\-brightness\fR \fIPCT\fR
Per-key brightness 0\(en100% (default: 100). Maps to firmware levels 0\(en5.
When used alone (without \fB\-\-set\fR/\fB\-\-hsv\fR), updates brightness
without re-uploading per-key data.
.PP
.B Named groups:
\fBfrow\fR, \fBnumrow\fR, \fBqrow\fR, \fBhomerow\fR, \fBshiftrow\fR,
\fBbottom\fR, \fBarrows\fR, \fBnav\fR, \fBsyskeys\fR, \fBnumpad\fR,
\fBwasd\fR, \fBalphas\fR, \fBmods\fR, \fBall\fR.
.SS solid
Fill the display with a solid colour.
.PP
.RS 4
.B ajazz solid
[\fB\-r\fR \fIN\fR] [\fB\-g\fR \fIN\fR] [\fB\-b\fR \fIN\fR]
.RE
.PP
Options \fB\-r\fR/\fB\-g\fR/\fB\-b\fR are the same as for \fBlight\fR.
Defaults are red=255, green=0, blue=0.
.SS image
Upload a static image to the display. The image is scaled to 240\[mu]135 pixels.
.PP
.RS 4
.B ajazz image
[\fB\-\-fill\fR]
.I FILE
.RE
.PP
Accepted formats: PNG, JPG, BMP, GIF (first frame only), and pre-converted
\fB.raw\fR files (256-byte header followed by RGB565-LE pixel data).
.TP
\fB\-\-fill\fR
Scale to fill the display with centre-crop (no black bars, edges may be clipped).
Without this flag, the image is letterboxed to preserve aspect ratio.
.SS animation
Upload an animated GIF to the display. The firmware supports a maximum of
141 frames; longer animations are truncated automatically. Frame delays outside
the range 2\(en510\~ms are clamped. A progress bar is shown during the upload,
which takes roughly 78\~seconds for a 141-frame animation.
.PP
.RS 4
.B ajazz animation
[\fB\-\-fill\fR]
.I FILE
.RE
.PP
Accepts the same formats as \fBimage\fR plus multi-frame GIFs.
\fB\-\-fill\fR behaves identically to the \fBimage\fR subcommand.
.SH CONFIGURATION
.SS Udev rules
The file \fI/etc/udev/rules.d/99-ajazz-ak35i.rules\fR grants access to the
keyboard's HID devices without root privileges:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
SUBSYSTEM=="hidraw", ATTRS{idVendor}=="0c45", ATTRS{idProduct}=="8009", \\
    MODE="0660", GROUP="plugdev", TAG+="uaccess"
.fi
.RE
.PP
The \fBTAG+="uaccess"\fR rule automatically grants access to the logged-in
local desktop user via \fBsystemd-logind\fR(8). For SSH or non-seat sessions,
add yourself to the \fBplugdev\fR group and re-login:
.PP
.RS 4
sudo usermod \-aG plugdev "$USER"
.RE
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Parse error, device not found, or runtime failure (message printed to stderr).
.SH EXAMPLES
List detected interfaces:
.PP
.RS 4
.B ajazz list
.RE
.PP
Sync the clock to the current time:
.PP
.RS 4
.B ajazz time
.RE
.PP
Set solid red backlighting with breathing animation at half speed:
.PP
.RS 4
.B ajazz light \-m breath \-r 255 \-g 0 \-b 0 \-\-speed 2
.RE
.PP
Cycle through the full colour spectrum:
.PP
.RS 4
.B ajazz light \-m spectrum \-\-rainbow
.RE
.PP
Fill the display with black (clear it):
.PP
.RS 4
.B ajazz solid \-r 0 \-g 0 \-b 0
.RE
.PP
Upload a photo, letterboxed to fit:
.PP
.RS 4
.B ajazz image photo.jpg
.RE
.PP
Upload a photo scaled to fill the screen:
.PP
.RS 4
.B ajazz image \-\-fill photo.jpg
.RE
.PP
Upload an animated GIF:
.PP
.RS 4
.B ajazz animation loop.gif
.RE
.PP
Show live per-key colours:
.PP
.RS 4
.B ajazz keys
.RE
.PP
Set WASD keys to red (read-modify-write, other keys unchanged):
.PP
.RS 4
.B ajazz keys \-\-set wasd red
.RE
.PP
Dim blue base with red WASD:
.PP
.RS 4
.B ajazz keys \-\-base 0 0 20 \-\-set wasd 255 0 0
.RE
.PP
Build a layout from scratch (all-off, then green F-row, red WASD):
.PP
.RS 4
.B ajazz keys \-\-clear \-\-set frow 0 200 0 \-\-set wasd 255 0 0
.RE
.PP
Rainbow rows using HSV:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
ajazz keys \-\-clear \\
  \-\-hsv frow 0 255 200 \\
  \-\-hsv numrow 30 255 200 \\
  \-\-hsv qrow 85 255 200 \\
  \-\-hsv homerow 128 255 200 \\
  \-\-hsv shiftrow 170 255 200 \\
  \-\-hsv bottom 213 255 200
.fi
.RE
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/udev/rules.d/99-ajazz-ak35i.rules
udev rules granting unprivileged HID access.
.SH NOTES
This is an unofficial, community-written tool with no affiliation with Ajazz or
the keyboard's manufacturer. The HID protocol was reverse-engineered; see
\fIPROTOCOL.md\fR in the source distribution for details.
.PP
Display content and lighting settings are stored in the keyboard's flash memory
and survive power cycles.
.SH BUGS
Report issues at the project repository on GitHub.
